# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2009-colorado-rockies-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The **1992 Major League Baseball expansion draft** was held on November 17, 1992, in New York City.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The expansion draft allowed two expansion teams in Major League Baseball (MLB)—the Colorado Rockies and Florida Marlins—to build their rosters prior to their inaugural seasons.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The 1990 collective bargaining agreement between MLB owners and the MLB Players Association allowed the National League (NL) to expand by two members—from 12 to 14—to match the size of the American League (AL).
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] In June 1991, MLB accepted bids of groups from Miami, Florida, and Denver, Colorado, with debuts set for the 1993 season.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Rockies were placed in the NL West division and the Marlins were placed in the NL East division.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] This was the first major-league expansion draft that allowed expansion teams to select players from either league.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Marlins and Rockies used the draft to build their teams using different strategies.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] As the Rockies had a smaller operating budget than the Marlins, the Rockies targeted prospects with low salaries, while the Marlins selected older players intended to provide more immediate impact.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] All three rounds of the draft were televised by ESPN.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Major League Baseball (MLB) team owners and the MLB Players Association agreed to expand the National League (NL) by two teams in the 1990 collective bargaining agreement.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Prior to expansion, the NL had 12 teams while the American League had 14.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] In June 1991, MLB accepted two bids for expansion franchises: one for Miami, Florida, and the other for Denver, Colorado.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Expansion was approved unanimously by all teams in July 1991.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Denver group chose to call their franchise the Colorado Rockies, the same name used as the National Hockey League franchise that played in Denver from 1976 to 1982.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Miami group chose to call themselves the Florida Marlins to broaden their fanbase to the entire state, while reviving the nickname of the Miami Marlins, a defunct Minor League Baseball team.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] An expansion draft to stock both franchises was set for November 1992.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] In contrast to previous expansion drafts, players from both the American League (AL) and National League (NL) were available to the expansion clubs.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Each existing club could protect 15 players on their 40-man roster from being drafted and only one player could be drafted from each team in each round.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] At the end of each round, NL teams could protect an additional three players and AL teams could protect an additional four.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] To further protect the AL teams, a maximum of eight AL teams could have three players chosen.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] All unprotected MLB and minor league players were eligible except those chosen in the amateur drafts of 1991 or 1992 and players who were 18 or younger when signed in 1990.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Players who were free agents after the 1992 season were not eligible for selection in the draft.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Rockies and Marlins, however, were not restricted in offering contracts to free agents.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Rockies signed their first free agent, Andrés Galarraga, to a one-year contract the day before the expansion draft.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Colorado won the toss and chose to pick first overall.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The three rounds of the draft were televised by ESPN.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] With the first pick, the Rockies chose David Nied, who had a 3–0 win–loss record with a 1.17 earned run average in six MLB appearances with the Atlanta Braves.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Marlins' first selection, Nigel Wilson, spent the 1992 season with the Double-A Knoxville Smokies of the Toronto Blue Jays organization, and had no MLB experience.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] In total, the Rockies and Marlins chose 41 pitchers with their combined 72 selections.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Of the 72 players chosen, 11 were All-Stars during their careers.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Jack Armstrong, Bryan Harvey, and Danny Jackson had been All-Stars before the expansion draft, while Andy Ashby, Brad Ausmus, Vinny Castilla, Jeff Conine, Carl Everett, Joe Girardi, Harvey, Trevor Hoffman, Jackson, and Eric Young became All-Stars later on in their careers.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Hoffman would also be elected to the Hall of Fame in 2018.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Several older star players who were left unprotected, including Danny Tartabull, Jack Morris, and Shawon Dunston, were not selected due to their high salaries and advanced age.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Based on the results of the expansion draft, the Marlins were projected to have a higher payroll in 1993 than the Rockies.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Rockies' payroll appeared to be $4 million, less than what the Marlins would pay Bryan Harvey.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The New York Yankees challenged the validity of the draft on the basis that the Marlins did not compensate the Yankees for the loss of territory in Fort Lauderdale, Florida, where the Yankees had a minor league team.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] They attempted to revoke the assignment of Hayes and Ausmus to the Rockies and Everett to the Marlins.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Invoking the "best interests of baseball" clause, Commissioner Bud Selig and the major league executive council affirmed the draft results.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] In the 1993 Major League Baseball season, the Marlins and Rockies both finished sixth out of seven teams in their respective divisions.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Rockies were the first team to reach the playoffs, using the roster they developed through the expansion draft to win the wild card in 1995, a record for the shortest amount of time for an expansion baseball team to make the playoffs at the time.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] (The Arizona Diamondbacks would go on to break the record by reaching the playoffs in 1999, their second year of existence.) Ritz and Painter, both selected in the expansion draft, started Games 1 and 2 of the 1995 National League Division Series for the Rockies.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Rockies added free agent acquisition Larry Walker to a lineup of power hitters in Galarraga, Bichette, and Castilla, known collectively as the "Blake Street Bombers".
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Meanwhile, the Marlins kept fewer players they selected in the expansion draft than the Rockies.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] In 1996, the Rockies retained 13 players from the draft, while the Marlins had six.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Marlin", was the only player selected in the expansion draft on the Marlins' 1997 World Series championship roster.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] However, the Marlins used the players selected in the expansion draft to craft their 1997 roster.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The Marlins traded three players selected in the draft, Hoffman, Martínez and Berumen, to the San Diego Padres for Gary Sheffield, a key member of the 1997 Florida Marlins.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] However, other key players to the Marlins' World Series championship were signed as free agents.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1992-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The 1997 Marlins set records by reaching and winning the World Series in the team's fifth year (these records were broken by the 2001 Arizona Diamondbacks, who won the World Series in their fourth year of existence) and were the first wild card team to win the World Series.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] The **1993 Colorado Rockies season** was the inaugural season for the expansion team in Major League Baseball (MLB) located in Denver, Colorado, which were established as a member of the National League (NL), competing in the NL West division, and based at Mile High Stadium.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] The first manager named for the Rockies was Don Baylor.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] First baseman Andrés Galarraga represented the Rockies at the MLB All-Star Game, held at Oriole Park at Camden Yards.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] Colorado finished with a record of 67–95, in sixth place and 37 games behind the NL West division-champion and NL pennant-winning Atlanta Braves, ahead of only the San Diego Padres.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] At Mile High Stadium, better known as the home of the Denver Broncos of the National Football League (NFL), the Rockies sold 4,483,350 tickets to their home games, setting the Major League record for attendance, which still stands as of the 2023 season.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] Galarraga concluded the season winning the NL batting title with a .370 batting average, also leading the major leagues.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] Shortstop Vinny Castilla was the last player from the Rockies' inaugural season to retire, playing his last game at the end of 2006.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] As opposed to previous expansion drafts such as the 1961 draft, players from both leagues were available to the expansion clubs.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] Each existing club could protect fifteen players on their roster from being drafted and only one player could be drafted from each team in the first round.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] Then for each additional round National League teams could protect an additional 3 players and American League teams could protect 4 more.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] All unprotected major and minor League players were eligible except those chosen in the amateur drafts of 1991 or 1992 and players who were 18 or younger when signed in 1990.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] The Rockies and Florida Marlins, set to debut in 1993, were allowed to participate in all rounds of the June 1992 MLB first-year player draft.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] The Rockies selected 27th overall in the first round, with pitcher John Burke their top pick.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] Of the 50 amateur free agents selected, ten made the major leagues, including Burke and—most prominently—Craig Counsell (11th round) and Quinton McCracken (25th).
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-colorado-rockies-season] The Rockies affiliated with two minor league clubs during 1992 to develop drafted players.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The **1993 Major League Baseball expansion** resulted in Major League Baseball (MLB) adding two expansion teams to the National League (NL) for the 1993 season: the Colorado Rockies and the Florida Marlins (now known as the Miami Marlins).
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Talks of expansion began on August 8, 1985, when the players and the owners agreed to a new collective bargaining agreement (CBA).
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The basic agreement allowed the National League to expand by two members to match the American League, which had done so in 1977.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Details of expansion were finalized in the 1990 CBA.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Ten cities were considered serious candidates for the two spots: Buffalo, Charlotte, Denver, Miami, Nashville, Orlando, Phoenix, Sacramento, Tampa Bay, and Washington.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Petersburg and Pilot Field in Buffalo were built specifically to lure an existing or expansion MLB franchise.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The National League expansion committee consisted of Pittsburgh Pirates Chairman Doug Danfort, New York Mets president Fred Wilpon and Houston Astros owner John McMullen.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] On December 18, 1990, the committee eliminated Charlotte, Nashville, Phoenix and Sacramento from consideration to cut the list down to six finalists.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] With three sites from Florida remaining in contention it became apparent that one would win out while the other spot would go to a non-Florida team.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] After previous failed attempts to bring Major League Baseball to the state of Colorado (most notably the Pittsburgh Pirates nearly relocating to Denver following the Pittsburgh drug trials in 1985), by the late 1980s a team seemed to be a possibility in Denver.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Eugene Orza, associate general counsel of the Major League Baseball Players Association, stated that he expected Denver would receive one of the expansion franchises.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Colorado Baseball Commission, led by banking executive Larry Varnell, was successful in getting Denver voters to approve a 0.1% sales tax to help finance a new baseball stadium.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Also, an advisory committee was formed in 1990 by then-Governor of Colorado Roy Romer to recruit an ownership group.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The group selected was led by John Antonucci, an Ohio beverage distributor, and Michael I.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Monus, the head of the Phar-Mor drugstore chain.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Local and regional companies—such as Erie Lake, Hensel Phelps Construction, KOA Radio, and the *Rocky Mountain News*—rounded out the group.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Senator Connie Mack III from Florida, the grandson of baseball great Connie Mack and a member of the Senate Task Force on Major League Baseball, pushed Baseball Commissioner Fay Vincent to expand to Florida.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] On March 7, 1990, Wayne Huizenga, CEO of Blockbuster Entertainment Corporation, announced he had purchased 15% of the NFL's Miami Dolphins and 50% of the Dolphins' home, Joe Robbie Stadium, for an estimated $30 million.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Huizenga stated his intention to aggressively pursue an expansion franchise.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] MLB had announced a few months earlier that it intended to add two new teams to the National League.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] It was a foregone conclusion that one of them would be placed in Florida; the only question was whether Huizenga would beat out competing groups from Orlando and Tampa Bay.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Orlando fielded a very spirited campaign bolstered by its family-oriented tourism industry.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Tampa Bay already had a baseball park — the Florida Suncoast Dome in St.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] On June 10, 1990, Huizenga was awarded an expansion franchise in the National League (NL) for a $95 million expansion fee and the team began operations in 1993 as the Florida Marlins.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] In June 1991, the expansion committee accepted the bids of the Miami and Denver groups to debut in 1993.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Though previous expansions allowed the drafting of players from the same league only, Vincent declared that the American League would receive $42 million of the National League's $190 million in expansion revenue so that the AL would provide players in the National League expansion draft.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] In an attempt to win support in the American League and balance the vote, Vincent decreed that the AL owners were entitled to 22% of the $190 million take.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] This decision marked the first time in expansion history that leagues were required to share expansion revenue or provide players for another league's expansion draft.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Vincent said the owners expanded to raise money to pay their collusion debt.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Tampa Bay Baseball Group sued MLB for allegedly reneging on an agreement to grant an expansion team to Tampa.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The suit was settled in 2003, five years after Tampa's major league team, the Devil Rays (now simply the Rays), began play in the American League.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-season] The **1993 Major League Baseball season** was the final season of two-division play in each league, before central divisions were added the following season, giving both the National League (NL) and American League (AL) three divisions each.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-season] Sixteen years after the AL expanded from 12 to 14 teams, the NL finally followed suit, with the Colorado Rockies and the Florida Marlins (now the Miami Marlins) joining the NL.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-season] As a result, it was the first season since 1976 that both leagues had the same number of teams.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-season] The Toronto Blue Jays capped off the season by winning their second consecutive World Series title, beating the Philadelphia Phillies in six games.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series was clinched when, in one of the most famous moments in baseball history, Joe Carter hit a three-run walk-off home run in the bottom of the ninth inning of Game 6 to seal the victory.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season under MLB's four-year deals with CBS and ESPN.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-season] While ESPN renewed its contract, CBS declined.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1993-major-league-baseball-season] MLB would then form The Baseball Network, a joint venture with ABC and NBC, to replace CBS in televising games on broadcast television.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] The **1994 Colorado Rockies season** was their second as a Major League Baseball team, and their final season at Mile High Stadium.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] Managed by Don Baylor, they finished with a record of 53–64, third in the National League West and six and a half games back from the division leader.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] The season was cut short by a player strike.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] The Rockies had the highest home field attendance in the 1994 season, with over three million fans attending throughout the year.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] The team tied the White Sox for the most triples (39) in the majors that year.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] However, Rockies pitchers hit the most batters (49).
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] In April 1994, the Rockies played in a weekend exhibition game at BC Place in Vancouver.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] By Friday, August 12, the Rockies had compiled a 53-64 record through 117 games.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] They were drawing really well at home, with an attendance of 3,281,511 through 57 home games for an average of 57,570 per game.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] At that pace, the team would have had a good chance of drawing more than 4.6 million fans in their 81 home games if the season had continued.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] Offensively, the Rockies had scored 573 runs (4.90 per game) and allowed 638 runs (5.45 per game) prior to the strike.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] The Rockies tied the Chicago White Sox in 1994 for the most triples in the majors, with 39.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1994-colorado-rockies-season] Their pitchers, however, hit 49 batters: the most in the majors.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] The **1995 Colorado Rockies season** was their 3rd in Major League Baseball and their 1st season at Coors Field.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] The team competed in the National League West, finishing with a record of 77−67, second in the division.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] The Rockies simultaneously won the first-ever National League wild card berth in the first season of the revised postseason format and first postseason appearance in franchise history.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] They faced the eventual World Series champion Atlanta Braves in the National League Division Series (NLDS), who won this first round series in four games, with the Rockies taking game three.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] The start to the 1995 MLB regular season was delayed over three weeks by the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike that ended on April 2.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] As a result, the season only lasted 144 games (instead of the typical 162 game season) and "official" opening day for Coors Field was changed to April 26.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] The Colorado Rockies played two exhibition games on April 2 and 3 against the New York Yankees as the first baseball to be played at Coors Field.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] In his Rockies debut and inaugural game of Coors Field on April 26 versus the New York Mets, Larry Walker doubled three times, including one that tied the score with two outs in the ninth inning.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] Dante Bichette hit a walk-off home run in the fourteenth inning for an 11−9 win.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] On May 7, 1995, Walker hit his 100th career home run versus Hideo Nomo of Los Angeles.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] The Rockies led the NL in hits (1,406), runs scored (785), triples (43, also the most in the majors), home runs (200), runs batted in (749), batting average (.282) and slugging percentage (.471).
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] Conversely, they also allowed the most hits (1,443), runs (783), earned runs (711) and produced the fewest shutouts (1).
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] A quartet of Rockies hitters who became known as "The Blake Street Bombers", consisting of Dante Bichette, Vinny Castilla, Andrés Galarraga (Walker's former Expos teammate), and Larry Walker, each contributed at least 30 home runs in 1995.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] The Rockies simultaneously won the first-ever National League wild card berth under the revised postseason format and first playoff appearance in franchise history in just their third season of play.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] On October 1 for the final regular season game, the Rockies needed a win at Coors Field versus the San Francisco Giants to avoid playing a tie-breaker game with the Houston Astros for the National League Wild Card post-season berth.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] Using seven pitchers during the nine inning game, Curt Leskanic earned his 10th save and threw the final pitch of the game in a 10–9 victory for the Rockies.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] During a post-season interview, Leskanic recalled the pitching mound shaking like a mild earthquake with the vibrations from fans in the stadium anticipating their first ever appearance in the MLB post-season.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] During the playoffs, Larry Walker collected three hits in 14 at bats in the National League Division Series (NLDS) versus the Atlanta Braves.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] He hit his first career postseason home run off Tom Glavine in the sixth inning of a 7−4 Game 2 loss.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1995-colorado-rockies-season] The Braves defeated the Rockies in four games.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1996-colorado-rockies-season] The **Colorado Rockies' 1996 season** was the fourth for the Rockies.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/1996-colorado-rockies-season] Managed by Don Baylor, they played home games at Coors Field and finished with a record of 83–79, third in the National League West.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/2009-colorado-rockies-season] The **2009 Colorado Rockies** entered the season attempting to improve on their 74–88 record from 2008.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/2009-colorado-rockies-season] They lost 28 of their first 46 games, but following the hiring of interim manager Jim Tracy, the Rockies came back to win their third Wild Card title, and second in three years.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/2009-colorado-rockies-season] The Rockies had a chance to win the division on the final series of the season needing to win all three games against the Dodgers to do so, but lost the last two after winning the first game to lose out on the division title.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/2009-colorado-rockies-season] The team drew 2,665,080 fans for the season, their highest total since 2002.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/2009-colorado-rockies-season] The average home attendance was 32,902 fans.
[src:2009-colorado-rockies-season/2009-colorado-rockies-season] Their 92 regular season wins is currently the most in a single season in Rockies franchise history and their 715 runs allowed is the fewest runs they have allowed in a full season.
